article.headline: Virginia-native Lawson wows friendly crowd
article.linkText: Lawson, Lady Vols give Summitt win No. 798
article.story:
NORFOLK, Va. (AP) -- Kara Lawson had family in the crowd and
showed them what they came to see, scoring 19 points and putting on
a show to lead No. 5 Tennessee to a 91-63 victory Tuesday night
over Old Dominion.

The victory gave Pat Summitt her 798th career coaching victory
just three days after a crushing 63-62 overtime loss at No. 3
Connecticut.

"I think by far this was our best team effort all season,''
Lawson said after all 11 Lady Vols who played scored. "That's what
you want out of your bench -- you want to be able to go there and
not lose too much.

"They came in and kind of sparked the game.''

After worrying that her team wasn't over the loss to the
Huskies, Summitt saw quickly the focus she wanted. Ten players
scored by halftime.

"That was the best we've run our motion (offense) all year,''
she said. "We made the extra pass. We set more deliberate screens.
We had good reads and got good looks. I thought the bench brought a
lot of energy.''

So did Lawson, the 1999 national high school player of the year
and two-time state player of the year at West Springfield High
School in Alexandria. She had 11 of her 19 points in the first half
and hit a 3-pointer early in the second half that helped build a
winning 25-10 run.

"I know what I need to bring to the table for my team,'' she
said, adding that doing well in her lone game in Virginia made it
even better. "I watched Virginia and ODU growing up.

"Those are the programs I followed. I always get excited to
come here and play.''

Summitt's victory total is sixth among all coaches in men's or
women's college basketball. She's lost 161 times.

   "It's certainly not about me. It's about this team,'' she said
of the milestone 800 victories she's taken 29 years to approach.
"I hope I get it this year.''

The Lady Monarchs (4-5), who had won three straight, fell to 9-27 in their long-running rivalry against the six-time national champions.

Okeisha Howard led the way with 20 points for Old Dominion, but
said the aura of Tennessee might have toyed with the players'
confidence before the tipoff.

   "We tried too hard instead of letting the game come to us,''
she said. "We forced a lot of things that really weren't there,
and we came up with turnovers and Tennessee came up with fast
breaks.

"It gets in your head but you really can't let it get to you. But I think tonight it got to us a little bit.''

The Lady Vols led 24-22 late in the first half before Lawson hit
a 3-pointer from the top of the key with 5:39 to play to spark a 15-4 run.

A free throw by Shareese Grant pulled the Lady Monarchs to 39-27
at the break, but the Lady Vols got 3-pointers from Loree Moore and
Lawson early in the second half, and dominant inside play from
Ashley Robinson.

Robinson and Gwen Jackson had six points each during the big run
that started the half, and the Lady Vols extended their lead to as
many as 30.

Lawson made eight of 12 shots from the field, including three 3-pointers, and had seven assists. Robinson and Brittany Jackson added 13 points apiece, and Gwen Jackson had 12. The Lady Vols shot 56.3 percent from the field and limited the Lady Monarchs to 37.3-percent shooting.
